<a name="top"></a><center><H2>People Involved with EODG</H2><hr></center>

<center><img src="group2006-06-01.jpg" width=95%></center>

<p><a name="banks">Jamie Banks</a> D. Phil. Student at
AOPP. </br> Assimilation of tropospheric aerosol observations.</br> email: <IMG
SRC="emails/jamie.png" align="middle"></p>

<!--<p><a name="burgess">Alastair Burgess</a> D. Phil. Student at
AOPP. </br> Investigating trace gas retrievals from the MIPAS
satellite instrument. Especially concentrating on OCS, SO2, SF6 and
NH3. All these species are at the borderline of detectibility, but are
of interest to modelling and climate groups as their current profiles,
distributions and trends are not measured frequently.</br> email: <IMG
SRC="emails/alastair.png" align="middle"></p>-->

<p><a name="campmany">Elies Campmany</a> PostDoc at AOPP.</br>
  He is involved in the <a
  href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/grape">GRAPE</a> and <a
  href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/project/Quantify">QUANTIFY</a> projects
within the Earth Observation Data Group.
His research consists in create an algorithm to detect ship tracks in
ATSR2 Satellite Imagery. Ship tracks are formed in the marine boundary
layer of the atmosphere as a result of ship stack emissions.
</br> e-mail: <IMG SRC="emails/campmany.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="carboni">Elisa Carboni</a> PostDoc at AOPP.</br> My
research is focused on aerosol retrieval using remote sensing
measurements. In particular Im interested in the comparison and the
analysis of satellite and ground based data. The main purpose of my
work is to better characterize the aerosol optical properties and to
use those properties in radiative transfer computations in order to
produce aerosol maps from satellite data and reduce the uncertainties
present on the estimate of aerosol effects on Earth radiative balance.
</br> e-mail: <IMG SRC="emails/elisa.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="dudhia">Anu Dudhia</a> PostDoc at AOPP.</br> Coordinating
AOPP <a href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/mipas/>MIPAS work</a> and
involved in various ESA studies on MIPAS and future missions.
Responsible for the <a href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/RFM>RFM</a>
line-by-line radiative transfer model.</br> e-mail: <IMG SRC="emails/anu.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="grainger">Don Grainger</a> Lecturer in AOPP. </br> His
main interest is in using satellite instruments to determine
aerosol/cloud properties and trace gas concentrations in the Earth's
atmosphere. This includes studies into natural and anthropogenic
changes in atmospheric aerosols and clouds through process such as
volcanic emission, aircraft and ship pollution, and surface
erosion.</br> e-mail: <IMG SRC="emails/don.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="hurley">Jane Hurley</a> D.Phil student at AOPP.</br>
Jane's work focusses on modelling clouds in the infrared using the
ENVISAT MIPAS instrument.</br>
email: <IMG SRC="emails/jane.png" align="middle"> </p>

<p><a name="Irshad"> <IMG SRC="emails/RanahIrshad.png" ></a>
DPhil student at AOPP.</br>Currently involved in setting up and conducting laboratory measurements of
the optical properties of NaCl and sea salt aerosols using the Molecular
Spectroscopy Facility at RAL.
</br>
email: <IMG SRC="emails/ranah.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="miles">Georgina Miles</a> D.Phil student at AOPP.</br>
Georgina has interests in modelling the climate response to volcanic
aerosols and uncertainties in their measurement.  Her main research
concerns detection of volcanic SO2 using the HIRS instrument. <a
href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/gmiles/>Homepage</a>.</br> e-mail:
<IMG SRC="emails/georgina.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="millanvalle">Luis Millan Valle</a> D. Phil. Student at
AOPP. </br> Infrared limb sounding of the mesosphere using the HIRDLS and MIPAS satellite instruments</br> email: <IMG
SRC="emails/luis.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="peters">Dan Peters</a> PostDoc at AOPP.</br> Dan's research is currently
focussed on measuring the optical properties of
"solid" atmospheric aerosols, (such as volcanic ash and Saharan dust,)
using the <a href=http://www.ssd.rl.ac.uk/msf/>NERC Molecular
Spectroscopy Facility</a> at the <a
href=http://www.rl.ac.uk/>Rutherford Appleton Laboratory</a>. The main
motivation for these measurements is to aid the extension of current
retrieval algorithms to include atmospheric aerosols. This is
currently an important contribution to climate change
uncertainty. Other interests include the <a
href=http://aura.gsfc.nasa.gov/instruments/hirdls/introduction.html>HIRDLS</a>
instrument radiometric calibration and <a
href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/main/capabilities/blackbodies.html>high
accuracy space based thermometry</a>.</br> e-mail: <IMG
SRC="emails/dan.png" align="middle"></p>
 
<p><a name="piccolo">Chiara Piccolo</a> PostDoc at AOPP.</br> Chiara
is working on the project "Data Assimilation" for DARC (Data
Assimilation Research Centre), under the supervision of Dr. Clive
Rodgers.  <a href=http://darc.nerc.ac.uk/>DARC</a> is a Centre of
Excellence in Earth Observation. It has the following partners:
University of Reading, Oxford, Cambridge, Edinburgh and Rutherford
Appleton Laboratory.  DARC focuses on data assimilation for the
atmosphere, using model of atmospheric chemistry and dynamics to study
the impact of research satellite data on our understanding of the
atmosphere.  The purpose of my work is to develop techniques for
making the best use of infrared limb sounders such as ISAMS (Improved
Stratospheric and Mesospheric Sounder), MIPAS (Michelson
Interferometer for Passive Atmospheric Sounding) and HiRDLS (High
Resolution Dynamics Limb Sounding).  </br> e-mail: <IMG
SRC="emails/chiara.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a name="rodgers">Clive Rodgers</a> Senior Research Reader in
Physics.</br> Though now retired, Clive is still active in
research. His main research interests include radiative transfer,
molecular spectroscopy, the application of estimation theory to the
inverse problem of radiative transfer, and the application of
satellite data to stratospheric and mesospheric dynamics and
chemistry. Current projects include data assimilation <a
href=http://darc.nerc.ac.uk/>(DARC)</a>, and retrieval aspects of <a
href=http://tes.jpl.nasa.gov/>TES</a> and <a
href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/mipas/>MIPAS</a>.  <a
href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/rodgers/>Homepage</a>. </br> e-mail:
<IMG SRC="emails/clive.png" align="middle"></p>

<p><a href="http://www-atm.physics.ox.ac.uk/user/sayer/index.html">Andy Sayer<a name="sayer"></a></a> D.Phil student at AOPP.</br>
Andy is involved with aerosol retrievals from the Advanced Along Track Scanning Radiometer <a href="http://www.leos.le.ac.uk/aatsr/">(AATSR)</a> aboard <a href="http://envisat.esa.int/">Envisat</a>. He has been developing code to utilise the dual-view capabilities of the instrument and is currently looking into methods of modelling sea surface albedo. His departmental webpage is <a href="http://www-atm.physics.ox.ac.uk/user/sayer/index.html">here</a>.</br>
email: <IMG SRC="emails/andy.png" align="middle"> </p>

